  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Lord is enraged at such abominable doings. He will interfere, and put an end to them by scattering Judah among the heathen. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 22:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". And, behold, I smite my hand because of thy gain which thou hast made, and over thy bloodguiltiness which is in the midst of thee. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 22:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Will thy heart indeed stand firm, or will thy hands be strong for the day when I shall deal with thee? I Jehovah have spoken it, and also do it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 22:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". I will scatter thee among the nations, and disperse thee in the lands, and will utterly remove thine uncleanness from thee. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 22:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". And thou wilt be desecrated through thyself before the eyes of the nations, and know that I am Jehovah. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 22:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is closely connected with the preceding verse. This serves to explain the fact that the only sins mentioned as exciting the wrath of God are covetousness and blood-guiltiness. הכּה , as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " clearly shows, is a contracted expression for הכּה כּף אל (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 21:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and the smiting of the hands together is a gesture indicative of wrathful indignation. For the form דּמך, contracted from דּמיך, see the comm. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 16:45",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". - As ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 22:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " leads on to the threatening of judgment, so does ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 22:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " point in anticipation to the terrible nature of the judgment itself. The question, \"will thy heart stand firm?\" involves a warning against security. עמד is the opposite of נמס (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 21:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), as standing forms the antithesis to passing away (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 102:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). עשׂה אותך, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 16:59",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Lord will scatter them (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 12:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 20:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and remove the uncleanness of sin, namely, by purifying the people in exile (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 4:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). התם, from תּמם, to cause to cease, with מן, to take completely away. נחלתּ, Niphal of חלל fo lahpiN ,נחלתּ ., connected with לעיני גּוים, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 20:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", not from נחל, as many of the commentators who follow the Septuagint and Vulgate suppose. בּך, not in te, in thyself, but through thee, i.e., through thy sinful conduct and its consequences. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
